  "text": "The key result here is the observation that phages can remodel their host cell, even in the absence of a replicating or integrated genome. It has long been known that integrated prophages modulate host phenotypes via gene expression, including superinfection exclusion, toxin production, and the production of Acr proteins (Bondy-Denomy et al., 2013 [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . Furthermore, the Imm protein produced by the lytic phage T4 prevents other phages in the environment from infecting the cell that one phage is currently replicating within [CITATION_4] . This has been attributed to preventing sequential infections and the disruption of the carefully timed phage replication cycle. In contrast to these examples, Figure S2 .",
